While the way I made the setting helped make the reason for anthros appear feel realistic, it did kinda stifle too much behavioral quirks. Basically it's mice and rats, since they are genetically close to humans, that were used as the cure method. The physical changes were a bit less ideal (the middle generations weren't pretty; think hairless rodents with only half-formed tails, muzzles and such), but the fact the cure was so wide-spread, and the fact that if you have a single ancestor who was given said cure, that even if you have a kid with another human, there's a constant (albeit low) percentage that your kid will be an anthro (and vica versa; two anthros have a small chance of birthing a human, with mixed couples averaging 50/50). Everyone from the poorest couple to the richest can and will have rodent anthro kids, so it kinda helps curb any attempts at eugenics.

That said, I've tried to have some unique quirks tied to a more feral touch. The waifur suffers from a condition that is exclusive to said species which is an enhanced fight or flight sense, especially when alone (based on rodents apparently becoming desperate when isolated and more difficult to be reintroduced into the pack). Most of her kin with the condition freak out in an intense fashion, and the mouse versions are nervous and introverted by default, but the girl herself is heavily invested in the 'fight' side having trained in martial arts from an early age and it's been tied onto a case of PTSD she suffered as a kid. Basically when confronted, she will fight back, and fight damn well, even to a near suicidal fault. Part of the story is her and her lover (the human protagonist) working out their relationship and also making her more mentally sound.
